¹ This stone, with another near it, popularly called Little J ohn's Stone, was still in situ in the earlier part of the present century, and had a legend connected with it which may be met with in Oharlton, p. 146. Both stones have now been removed, and are, I was informed, set up again near the enclosing fence of the field in which they stood. Almost beyond question, like the other monoliths of the district, they marked the site of ancient British interments.
